<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1103,1540]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,384,1103,1129]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Diagnosis of male.</emphasis>
This species is easily recognized by the weak excision and slight angulate tooth on the ventral margin of the mandible (
<figureCitation box="[566,662,1141,1167]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 24" captionStartId="12.[151,275,1917,1941]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,381,1880]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,381,1896]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 24. Head, anterior view; except ventral view 17. 13. Odontophotopsis serca; 14. O. setifera; 15. Sphaeropthalma. amphion; 16. S. angulifera; 17. S. angulifera; 18. S. arota; 19. S. becki; 20. S. blakeii; 21. S. difficilis; 22. S. ferruginea; 23. S. ignacio; and 24. S. macswaini." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/196849/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[628,662,1141,1167]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="18.0">18</number>
</figureCitation>
), which is oblique apically, the clypeus carinate at base, but sometimes delicately so or gibbous (
<figureCitation box="[585,674,1178,1204]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 24" captionStartId="12.[151,275,1917,1941]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,381,1880]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,381,1896]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 24. Head, anterior view; except ventral view 17. 13. Odontophotopsis serca; 14. O. setifera; 15. Sphaeropthalma. amphion; 16. S. angulifera; 17. S. angulifera; 18. S. arota; 19. S. becki; 20. S. blakeii; 21. S. difficilis; 22. S. ferruginea; 23. S. ignacio; and 24. S. macswaini." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/196849/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
Fig. 
<number box="[642,674,1178,1204]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="18.0">18</number>
</figureCitation>
), the lack of mesosternal processes or a sternal felt line, and the ventral margin of the paramere with dense setae that are directed inward toward the cuspis (see Fig. 
<quantity box="[1360,1436,1216,1242]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" unit="in" value="100.0">100 in</quantity>
Pitts 
<emphasis box="[210,262,1253,1278]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[276,339,1253,1279]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2009.0">2009</number>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,1103,1540]" box="[197,1094,1290,1316]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,446,1290,1316]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Diagnosis of female.</emphasis>
Pitts 
<emphasis box="[513,572,1291,1316]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number box="[587,649,1290,1316]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" value="2009.0">2009</number>
) diagnosed the female of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
